[{"sha":"a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Parallel transitions: Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions (#20672)

* Land enableTransitionEntanglement changes

Leaving the flag though because I plan to reuse it for additional,
similar changes.

* Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions

Currently we always assign the same lane to all transitions. This means
if there are two pending transitions at the same time, neither
transition can finish until both can finish, even if they affect
completely separate parts of the UI.

The new approach is to assign a different lane to each consecutive
transition, by shifting the bit to the right each time. When we reach
the end of the bit range, we cycle back to the first bit. In practice,
this should mean that all transitions get their own dedicated lane,
unless we have more pending transitions than lanes, which should
be rare.

We retain our existing behavior of assigning the same lane to all
transitions within the same event. This is achieved by caching the first
lane assigned to a transition, then re-using that one until the next
React task, by which point the event must have finished. This preserves
the guarantee that all transition updates that result from a single
event will be consistent.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/gaearon/react/commits/a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62"},{"sha":"b4658f2daa4990ef8057335cd7202b479bd8d41a","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@gmail.com"},"message":"Reduce some constant duplication (#20761)

* Fix lint","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MichaelDeBoey/react/commits/77754ae6183197a63716202f71be5d396f0f2b9a"},{"sha":"a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Parallel transitions: Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions (#20672)

* Land enableTransitionEntanglement changes

Leaving the flag though because I plan to reuse it for additional,
similar changes.

* Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions

Currently we always assign the same lane to all transitions. This means
if there are two pending transitions at the same time, neither
transition can finish until both can finish, even if they affect
completely separate parts of the UI.

The new approach is to assign a different lane to each consecutive
transition, by shifting the bit to the right each time. When we reach
the end of the bit range, we cycle back to the first bit. In practice,
this should mean that all transitions get their own dedicated lane,
unless we have more pending transitions than lanes, which should
be rare.

We retain our existing behavior of assigning the same lane to all
transitions within the same event. This is achieved by caching the first
lane assigned to a transition, then re-using that one until the next
React task, by which point the event must have finished. This preserves
the guarantee that all transition updates that result from a single
event will be consistent.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MichaelDeBoey/react/commits/a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62"},{"sha":"b4658f2daa4990ef8057335cd7202b479bd8d41a","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@gmail.com"},"message":"Reduce some constant duplication (#20761)

Because we have access to the artifacts in CI, we can read bundle sizes
directly from the filesystem, instead of the JSON files emitted by our
custom Rollup plugin.

This gives us some flexibility if we ever have artifacts that aren't
generated by Rollup, or if we rewrite our build script.

Personally, I also prefer to see the whole file path, instead of just
the name, because some of our names are repeated.

My immediate motivation, though, is because it gives us a way to merge
the separate "experimental" and "stable" size results. Instead
everything is reported in a single table and disambiguated by path.

I also added a section at the top that always displays the size impact
to certain critical bundles — right now, that's the React DOM production
bundles for each release channel. This section will also include any
size changes larger than 2%.

[{"sha":"680c021717eb5c082e4de13da0e479c1d8eacd05","author":{"name":"Kristofer Jonsson","email":"0d86e8af2c329a2fff8e85e6b330e5ad703be663@arm.com"},"message":"TFLu CMake build system prototype

This patch adds a CMake based build system for Tensorflow Lite for
Microcontrollers. The build system is provided for demonostration
purpose, to show what a CMake based build system could look
like.

This patch includes:
  - Building the microlite library.
  - Building unit tests and how to run them with CTest.
  - How to download 3rd parties.
  - Cross compiling with GCC and Arm Clang.

CMake brings many benefits, but perhaps the most importent advantage
is that CMake allows TFLu to be included by a parent CMake project
and cross compiled using a common toolchain file.

CMake runs on several host platforms, including Linux, Windows
and MacOS.

Change-Id: I5a632a7bcb8fc354c70b474dc0d2f6b25a3c0ab6

Add Sparkfun edge target

Adding target that demonstrates how the Tensorflow CMake project
can be included from a parent project.

This target shows how to preset default parameters and how to provide
a custom toolchain file tailored for this target.

When user supplies env-vars through kumactl, they are being added to the default list of env-vars instead of replacing them.
This fix makes sure the supplied env-vars get overridden properly if the env-var exists in default list otherwise they are added to the list.

* Create new template in _helpers.tpl and use it to generate env-vars in cp-deployment.yaml
* Update helmtemplates_vfsdata.go, since cp-deployment.yaml changed
* Update install-control-plane test cases, since generation of env-vars changed
* Add new test case in install-control-plane to test the fix

Fix #1273

(#1448)

When specifying a `kuma.io/service` with a "." DNS resolution would not work
because it would only look at the first part of the DNS name.
This would also cause `foo.bar.mesh` and `foo.mesh` to resolve to the same thing
which may give a false sense of isolation of meshes in the DNS
We now only strips the last part of the DNS name if it matches the `.mesh` domain suffix.

* feat(kumactl) add kumactl install crds cmd

- Introduced new `kumactl` command: `kumactl install crds`
  which will render all Custom Resource Definitions used by kuma.
  By providing `--only-missing` flag it will output content of
  CRDs which are not present in the cluster (it will use the same
  approach to get kubeconfig as `kumactl install control-plane`
  - I added small script which I will be using in helm hooks
    to generate missing CRDs. I'm doing it via script, and not by
    directly providing `entrypoint` or `cmd` to container, as there
    is logic to check if command `kumactl install crds \
     --only-missing` returns anything as if there are already
    all CRDs present the command `kubectl create -f -` would fail
    and I don't see any other, easier way to handle this case
- Added helm's pre-upgrade hook to install missing crds, which is
  using the container with `kumactl` mentioned above
- Modified helm's `values.yaml` file to reflect changes mentioned
  above

* fix(kumactl) fix sh scripts (removed function key)

Updated .golden files to reflect the new command
`kumactl install crds`

* feat(*) add helm upgrade logic to e2e framework

Introduced to our e2e tests framework functionalities to upgrade
kuma helm charts.

* fix(*) add helm repo for kuma in CI

As we currently are using our external helm repository, to install
some older versions of Kuma during the helm upgrade tests,
we have to configure helm to use this repository first

* feat(kumactl) introuce ctx to install crds command

[{"sha":"e96143ed6764d7bb1ba3524cfafdfaaf07598a66","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions

Currently we always assign the same lane to all transitions. This means
if there are two pending transitions at the same time, neither
transition can finish until both can finish, even if they affect
completely separate parts of the UI.

The new approach is to assign a different lane to each consecutive
transition, by shifting the bit to the right each time. When we reach
the end of the bit range, we cycle back to the first bit. In practice,
this should mean that all transitions get their own dedicated lane,
unless we have more pending transitions than lanes, which should
be rare.

We retain our existing behavior of assigning the same lane to all
transitions within the same event. This is achieved by caching the first
lane assigned to a transition, then re-using that one until the next
React task, by which point the event must have finished. This preserves
the guarantee that all transition updates that result from a single
event will be consistent.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/e96143ed6764d7bb1ba3524cfafdfaaf07598a66"}]

* Land enableTransitionEntanglement changes

Leaving the flag though because I plan to reuse it for additional,
similar changes.

* Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions

Currently we always assign the same lane to all transitions. This means
if there are two pending transitions at the same time, neither
transition can finish until both can finish, even if they affect
completely separate parts of the UI.

The new approach is to assign a different lane to each consecutive
transition, by shifting the bit to the right each time. When we reach
the end of the bit range, we cycle back to the first bit. In practice,
this should mean that all transitions get their own dedicated lane,
unless we have more pending transitions than lanes, which should
be rare.

We retain our existing behavior of assigning the same lane to all
transitions within the same event. This is achieved by caching the first
lane assigned to a transition, then re-using that one until the next
React task, by which point the event must have finished. This preserves
the guarantee that all transition updates that result from a single
event will be consistent.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/CrazyForks/react/commits/a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62"},{"sha":"b4658f2daa4990ef8057335cd7202b479bd8d41a","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@gmail.com"},"message":"Reduce some constant duplication (#20761)

* Land enableTransitionEntanglement changes

Leaving the flag though because I plan to reuse it for additional,
similar changes.

* Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions

Currently we always assign the same lane to all transitions. This means
if there are two pending transitions at the same time, neither
transition can finish until both can finish, even if they affect
completely separate parts of the UI.

The new approach is to assign a different lane to each consecutive
transition, by shifting the bit to the right each time. When we reach
the end of the bit range, we cycle back to the first bit. In practice,
this should mean that all transitions get their own dedicated lane,
unless we have more pending transitions than lanes, which should
be rare.

We retain our existing behavior of assigning the same lane to all
transitions within the same event. This is achieved by caching the first
lane assigned to a transition, then re-using that one until the next
React task, by which point the event must have finished. This preserves
the guarantee that all transition updates that result from a single
event will be consistent.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/stackriot/react/commits/a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62"}]

[{"sha":"77754ae6183197a63716202f71be5d396f0f2b9a","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@gmail.com"},"message":"Decouple event priority list from event name list (#20760)

* Remove some dead code

* Decouple event priority list from event name list

* Fix lint","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/suddenlyGiovanni/react/commits/77754ae6183197a63716202f71be5d396f0f2b9a"},{"sha":"a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Parallel transitions: Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions (#20672)

* Land enableTransitionEntanglement changes

Leaving the flag though because I plan to reuse it for additional,
similar changes.

* Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions

Currently we always assign the same lane to all transitions. This means
if there are two pending transitions at the same time, neither
transition can finish until both can finish, even if they affect
completely separate parts of the UI.

The new approach is to assign a different lane to each consecutive
transition, by shifting the bit to the right each time. When we reach
the end of the bit range, we cycle back to the first bit. In practice,
this should mean that all transitions get their own dedicated lane,
unless we have more pending transitions than lanes, which should
be rare.

We retain our existing behavior of assigning the same lane to all
transitions within the same event. This is achieved by caching the first
lane assigned to a transition, then re-using that one until the next
React task, by which point the event must have finished. This preserves
the guarantee that all transition updates that result from a single
event will be consistent.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/suddenlyGiovanni/react/commits/a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62"}]

(#1448)

When specifying a `kuma.io/service` with a "." DNS resolution would not work
because it would only look at the first part of the DNS name.
This would also cause `foo.bar.mesh` and `foo.mesh` to resolve to the same thing
which may give a false sense of isolation of meshes in the DNS
We now only strips the last part of the DNS name if it matches the `.mesh` domain suffix.

* Land enableTransitionEntanglement changes

Leaving the flag though because I plan to reuse it for additional,
similar changes.

* Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions

Currently we always assign the same lane to all transitions. This means
if there are two pending transitions at the same time, neither
transition can finish until both can finish, even if they affect
completely separate parts of the UI.

The new approach is to assign a different lane to each consecutive
transition, by shifting the bit to the right each time. When we reach
the end of the bit range, we cycle back to the first bit. In practice,
this should mean that all transitions get their own dedicated lane,
unless we have more pending transitions than lanes, which should
be rare.

We retain our existing behavior of assigning the same lane to all
transitions within the same event. This is achieved by caching the first
lane assigned to a transition, then re-using that one until the next
React task, by which point the event must have finished. This preserves
the guarantee that all transition updates that result from a single
event will be consistent.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JackEasons/react/commits/a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62"}]

(#1448)

When specifying a `kuma.io/service` with a "." DNS resolution would not work
because it would only look at the first part of the DNS name.
This would also cause `foo.bar.mesh` and `foo.mesh` to resolve to the same thing
which may give a false sense of isolation of meshes in the DNS
We now only strips the last part of the DNS name if it matches the `.mesh` domain suffix.

* Remove some dead code

* Decouple event priority list from event name list

* Fix lint","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/wadezhan/react/commits/77754ae6183197a63716202f71be5d396f0f2b9a"},{"sha":"a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Parallel transitions: Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions (#20672)

* Land enableTransitionEntanglement changes

Leaving the flag though because I plan to reuse it for additional,
similar changes.

* Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions

Currently we always assign the same lane to all transitions. This means
if there are two pending transitions at the same time, neither
transition can finish until both can finish, even if they affect
completely separate parts of the UI.

The new approach is to assign a different lane to each consecutive
transition, by shifting the bit to the right each time. When we reach
the end of the bit range, we cycle back to the first bit. In practice,
this should mean that all transitions get their own dedicated lane,
unless we have more pending transitions than lanes, which should
be rare.

We retain our existing behavior of assigning the same lane to all
transitions within the same event. This is achieved by caching the first
lane assigned to a transition, then re-using that one until the next
React task, by which point the event must have finished. This preserves
the guarantee that all transition updates that result from a single
event will be consistent.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/wadezhan/react/commits/a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62"}]

* feat(kumactl) add kumactl install crds cmd

- Introduced new `kumactl` command: `kumactl install crds`
  which will render all Custom Resource Definitions used by kuma.
  By providing `--only-missing` flag it will output content of
  CRDs which are not present in the cluster (it will use the same
  approach to get kubeconfig as `kumactl install control-plane`
  - I added small script which I will be using in helm hooks
    to generate missing CRDs. I'm doing it via script, and not by
    directly providing `entrypoint` or `cmd` to container, as there
    is logic to check if command `kumactl install crds \
     --only-missing` returns anything as if there are already
    all CRDs present the command `kubectl create -f -` would fail
    and I don't see any other, easier way to handle this case
- Added helm's pre-upgrade hook to install missing crds, which is
  using the container with `kumactl` mentioned above
- Modified helm's `values.yaml` file to reflect changes mentioned
  above

* fix(kumactl) fix sh scripts (removed function key)

Updated .golden files to reflect the new command
`kumactl install crds`

* feat(*) add helm upgrade logic to e2e framework

Introduced to our e2e tests framework functionalities to upgrade
kuma helm charts.

* fix(*) add helm repo for kuma in CI

As we currently are using our external helm repository, to install
some older versions of Kuma during the helm upgrade tests,
we have to configure helm to use this repository first

* feat(kumactl) introuce ctx to install crds command

* Remove some dead code

* Decouple event priority list from event name list

* Fix lint","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JochLAin/react/commits/77754ae6183197a63716202f71be5d396f0f2b9a"},{"sha":"a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Parallel transitions: Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions (#20672)

* Land enableTransitionEntanglement changes

Leaving the flag though because I plan to reuse it for additional,
similar changes.

* Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions

Currently we always assign the same lane to all transitions. This means
if there are two pending transitions at the same time, neither
transition can finish until both can finish, even if they affect
completely separate parts of the UI.

The new approach is to assign a different lane to each consecutive
transition, by shifting the bit to the right each time. When we reach
the end of the bit range, we cycle back to the first bit. In practice,
this should mean that all transitions get their own dedicated lane,
unless we have more pending transitions than lanes, which should
be rare.

We retain our existing behavior of assigning the same lane to all
transitions within the same event. This is achieved by caching the first
lane assigned to a transition, then re-using that one until the next
React task, by which point the event must have finished. This preserves
the guarantee that all transition updates that result from a single

* Fix lint","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/zys-contrib/react/commits/77754ae6183197a63716202f71be5d396f0f2b9a"},{"sha":"a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Parallel transitions: Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions (#20672)

* Land enableTransitionEntanglement changes

Leaving the flag though because I plan to reuse it for additional,
similar changes.

* Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions

Currently we always assign the same lane to all transitions. This means
if there are two pending transitions at the same time, neither
transition can finish until both can finish, even if they affect
completely separate parts of the UI.

The new approach is to assign a different lane to each consecutive
transition, by shifting the bit to the right each time. When we reach
the end of the bit range, we cycle back to the first bit. In practice,
this should mean that all transitions get their own dedicated lane,
unless we have more pending transitions than lanes, which should
be rare.

We retain our existing behavior of assigning the same lane to all
transitions within the same event. This is achieved by caching the first
lane assigned to a transition, then re-using that one until the next
React task, by which point the event must have finished. This preserves
the guarantee that all transition updates that result from a single
event will be consistent.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/zys-contrib/react/commits/a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62"}]

transition can finish until both can finish, even if they affect
completely separate parts of the UI.

be rare.

* Decouple event priority list from event name list

* Fix lint","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/linbingquan/react/commits/77754ae6183197a63716202f71be5d396f0f2b9a"},{"sha":"a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Parallel transitions: Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions (#20672)

* Land enableTransitionEntanglement changes

Leaving the flag though because I plan to reuse it for additional,
similar changes.

* Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions

Currently we always assign the same lane to all transitions. This means
if there are two pending transitions at the same time, neither
transition can finish until both can finish, even if they affect
completely separate parts of the UI.

The new approach is to assign a different lane to each consecutive
transition, by shifting the bit to the right each time. When we reach
the end of the bit range, we cycle back to the first bit. In practice,
this should mean that all transitions get their own dedicated lane,
unless we have more pending transitions than lanes, which should
be rare.

We retain our existing behavior of assigning the same lane to all
transitions within the same event. This is achieved by caching the first
lane assigned to a transition, then re-using that one until the next
React task, by which point the event must have finished. This preserves
the guarantee that all transition updates that result from a single
event will be consistent.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/linbingquan/react/commits/a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62"}]

* Decouple event priority list from event name list

* Fix lint","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tbergq/react/commits/77754ae6183197a63716202f71be5d396f0f2b9a"},{"sha":"a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Parallel transitions: Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions (#20672)

* Land enableTransitionEntanglement changes

Leaving the flag though because I plan to reuse it for additional,
similar changes.

* Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions

Currently we always assign the same lane to all transitions. This means
if there are two pending transitions at the same time, neither
transition can finish until both can finish, even if they affect
completely separate parts of the UI.

The new approach is to assign a different lane to each consecutive
transition, by shifting the bit to the right each time. When we reach
the end of the bit range, we cycle back to the first bit. In practice,
this should mean that all transitions get their own dedicated lane,
unless we have more pending transitions than lanes, which should
be rare.

We retain our existing behavior of assigning the same lane to all
transitions within the same event. This is achieved by caching the first
lane assigned to a transition, then re-using that one until the next
React task, by which point the event must have finished. This preserves
the guarantee that all transition updates that result from a single
event will be consistent.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tbergq/react/commits/a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62"}]

* feat(kumactl) add kumactl install crds cmd

- Introduced new `kumactl` command: `kumactl install crds`
  which will render all Custom Resource Definitions used by kuma.
  By providing `--only-missing` flag it will output content of
  CRDs which are not present in the cluster (it will use the same
  approach to get kubeconfig as `kumactl install control-plane`
  - I added small script which I will be using in helm hooks
    to generate missing CRDs. I'm doing it via script, and not by
    directly providing `entrypoint` or `cmd` to container, as there
    is logic to check if command `kumactl install crds \
     --only-missing` returns anything as if there are already
    all CRDs present the command `kubectl create -f -` would fail
    and I don't see any other, easier way to handle this case
- Added helm's pre-upgrade hook to install missing crds, which is
  using the container with `kumactl` mentioned above
- Modified helm's `values.yaml` file to reflect changes mentioned
  above

* fix(kumactl) fix sh scripts (removed function key)

Updated .golden files to reflect the new command
`kumactl install crds`

* feat(*) add helm upgrade logic to e2e framework

Introduced to our e2e tests framework functionalities to upgrade
kuma helm charts.

* fix(*) add helm repo for kuma in CI

As we currently are using our external helm repository, to install
some older versions of Kuma during the helm upgrade tests,
we have to configure helm to use this repository first

* Land enableTransitionEntanglement changes

Leaving the flag though because I plan to reuse it for additional,
similar changes.

* Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions

Currently we always assign the same lane to all transitions. This means
if there are two pending transitions at the same time, neither
transition can finish until both can finish, even if they affect
completely separate parts of the UI.

The new approach is to assign a different lane to each consecutive
transition, by shifting the bit to the right each time. When we reach
the end of the bit range, we cycle back to the first bit. In practice,
this should mean that all transitions get their own dedicated lane,
unless we have more pending transitions than lanes, which should
be rare.

We retain our existing behavior of assigning the same lane to all
transitions within the same event. This is achieved by caching the first
lane assigned to a transition, then re-using that one until the next
React task, by which point the event must have finished. This preserves
the guarantee that all transition updates that result from a single
event will be consistent.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Melon-Tropics/react/commits/a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62"},{"sha":"b4658f2daa4990ef8057335cd7202b479bd8d41a","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@gmail.com"},"message":"Reduce some constant duplication (#20761)

[{"sha":"261cf29afb9ed3f14038f7af27dc909117e29fb3","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions

Currently we always assign the same lane to all transitions. This means
if there are two pending transitions at the same time, neither
transition can finish until both can finish, even if they affect
completely separate parts of the UI.

The new approach is to assign a different lane to each consecutive
transition, by shifting the bit to the right each time. When we reach
the end of the bit range, we cycle back to the first bit. In practice,
this should mean that all transitions get their own dedicated lane,
unless we have more pending transitions than lanes, which should
be rare.

We retain our existing behavior of assigning the same lane to all
transitions within the same event. This is achieved by caching the first
lane assigned to a transition, then re-using that one until the next
React task, by which point the event must have finished. This preserves
the guarantee that all transition updates that result from a single
event will be consistent.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/261cf29afb9ed3f14038f7af27dc909117e29fb3"}]

[{"sha":"f02cb9fbbb55a44f02535d09ba334085d4c23112","author":{"name":"Kristofer Jonsson","email":"0d86e8af2c329a2fff8e85e6b330e5ad703be663@arm.com"},"message":"TFLu CMake build system prototype

This patch adds a CMake based build system for Tensorflow Lite for
Microcontrollers. The build system is provided for demonostration
purpose, to show what a CMake based build system could look
like.

This patch includes:
  - Building the microlite library.
  - Building unit tests and how to run them with CTest.
  - How to download 3rd parties.
  - Cross compiling with GCC and Arm Clang.

CMake brings many benefits, but perhaps the most importent advantage
is that CMake allows TFLu to be included by a parent CMake project
and cross compiled using a common toolchain file.

CMake runs on several host platforms, including Linux, Windows
and MacOS.

Change-Id: I5a632a7bcb8fc354c70b474dc0d2f6b25a3c0ab6

Add Sparkfun edge target

Adding target that demonstrates how the Tensorflow CMake project
can be included from a parent project.

This target shows how to preset default parameters and how to provide
a custom toolchain file tailored for this target.

* Land enableTransitionEntanglement changes

Leaving the flag though because I plan to reuse it for additional,

* Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions

Currently we always assign the same lane to all transitions. This means
if there are two pending transitions at the same time, neither
transition can finish until both can finish, even if they affect
completely separate parts of the UI.

The new approach is to assign a different lane to each consecutive
transition, by shifting the bit to the right each time. When we reach
the end of the bit range, we cycle back to the first bit. In practice,
this should mean that all transitions get their own dedicated lane,
unless we have more pending transitions than lanes, which should
be rare.

We retain our existing behavior of assigning the same lane to all
transitions within the same event. This is achieved by caching the first
lane assigned to a transition, then re-using that one until the next
React task, by which point the event must have finished. This preserves
the guarantee that all transition updates that result from a single

A running GMainLoop processes many events on the GLib/GStreamer
world. While some things may work without it, many others wont.
Examples of these are signals, timers and many other source
events. The problem becomes more concerning by the fact that
some GStreamer elements rely on signals to work.

* Land enableTransitionEntanglement changes

Leaving the flag though because I plan to reuse it for additional,
similar changes.

* Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions

Currently we always assign the same lane to all transitions. This means
if there are two pending transitions at the same time, neither
transition can finish until both can finish, even if they affect
completely separate parts of the UI.

The new approach is to assign a different lane to each consecutive
transition, by shifting the bit to the right each time. When we reach
the end of the bit range, we cycle back to the first bit. In practice,
this should mean that all transitions get their own dedicated lane,
unless we have more pending transitions than lanes, which should
be rare.

We retain our existing behavior of assigning the same lane to all
transitions within the same event. This is achieved by caching the first
lane assigned to a transition, then re-using that one until the next
React task, by which point the event must have finished. This preserves
the guarantee that all transition updates that result from a single
event will be consistent.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/react/commits/a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62"},{"sha":"b4658f2daa4990ef8057335cd7202b479bd8d41a","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@gmail.com"},"message":"Reduce some constant duplication (#20761)

* feat(kumactl) add kumactl install crds cmd

- Introduced new `kumactl` command: `kumactl install crds`
  which will render all Custom Resource Definitions used by kuma.
  By providing `--only-missing` flag it will output content of
  CRDs which are not present in the cluster (it will use the same
  approach to get kubeconfig as `kumactl install control-plane`
  - I added small script which I will be using in helm hooks
    to generate missing CRDs. I'm doing it via script, and not by
    directly providing `entrypoint` or `cmd` to container, as there
    is logic to check if command `kumactl install crds \
     --only-missing` returns anything as if there are already
    all CRDs present the command `kubectl create -f -` would fail
    and I don't see any other, easier way to handle this case
- Added helm's pre-upgrade hook to install missing crds, which is
  using the container with `kumactl` mentioned above
- Modified helm's `values.yaml` file to reflect changes mentioned
  above

* fix(kumactl) fix sh scripts (removed function key)

Updated .golden files to reflect the new command
`kumactl install crds`

* feat(*) add helm upgrade logic to e2e framework

* Fix lint","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/lancygoyal/react/commits/77754ae6183197a63716202f71be5d396f0f2b9a"},{"sha":"a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Parallel transitions: Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions (#20672)

* Land enableTransitionEntanglement changes

Leaving the flag though because I plan to reuse it for additional,
similar changes.

* Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions

Currently we always assign the same lane to all transitions. This means
if there are two pending transitions at the same time, neither
transition can finish until both can finish, even if they affect
completely separate parts of the UI.

The new approach is to assign a different lane to each consecutive
transition, by shifting the bit to the right each time. When we reach
the end of the bit range, we cycle back to the first bit. In practice,
this should mean that all transitions get their own dedicated lane,
unless we have more pending transitions than lanes, which should
be rare.

We retain our existing behavior of assigning the same lane to all
transitions within the same event. This is achieved by caching the first
lane assigned to a transition, then re-using that one until the next
React task, by which point the event must have finished. This preserves
the guarantee that all transition updates that result from a single
event will be consistent.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/lancygoyal/react/commits/a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62"}]

* feat(kumactl) add kumactl install crds cmd

- Introduced new `kumactl` command: `kumactl install crds`
  which will render all Custom Resource Definitions used by kuma.
  By providing `--only-missing` flag it will output content of
  CRDs which are not present in the cluster (it will use the same
  approach to get kubeconfig as `kumactl install control-plane`
  - I added small script which I will be using in helm hooks
    to generate missing CRDs. I'm doing it via script, and not by
    directly providing `entrypoint` or `cmd` to container, as there
    is logic to check if command `kumactl install crds \
     --only-missing` returns anything as if there are already
    all CRDs present the command `kubectl create -f -` would fail
    and I don't see any other, easier way to handle this case
- Added helm's pre-upgrade hook to install missing crds, which is
  using the container with `kumactl` mentioned above
- Modified helm's `values.yaml` file to reflect changes mentioned
  above

* fix(kumactl) fix sh scripts (removed function key)

Updated .golden files to reflect the new command
`kumactl install crds`

* feat(*) add helm upgrade logic to e2e framework

Introduced to our e2e tests framework functionalities to upgrade
kuma helm charts.

* fix(*) add helm repo for kuma in CI

As we currently are using our external helm repository, to install
some older versions of Kuma during the helm upgrade tests,
we have to configure helm to use this repository first

* feat(kumactl) introuce ctx to install crds command

* Fix lint","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/YashKumarVerma/react/commits/77754ae6183197a63716202f71be5d396f0f2b9a"},{"sha":"a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Parallel transitions: Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions (#20672)

* Land enableTransitionEntanglement changes

Leaving the flag though because I plan to reuse it for additional,
similar changes.

* Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions

Currently we always assign the same lane to all transitions. This means
if there are two pending transitions at the same time, neither
transition can finish until both can finish, even if they affect
completely separate parts of the UI.

The new approach is to assign a different lane to each consecutive
transition, by shifting the bit to the right each time. When we reach
the end of the bit range, we cycle back to the first bit. In practice,
this should mean that all transitions get their own dedicated lane,
unless we have more pending transitions than lanes, which should
be rare.

We retain our existing behavior of assigning the same lane to all
transitions within the same event. This is achieved by caching the first
lane assigned to a transition, then re-using that one until the next
React task, by which point the event must have finished. This preserves
the guarantee that all transition updates that result from a single
event will be consistent.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/YashKumarVerma/react/commits/a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62"},{"sha":"b4658f2daa4990ef8057335cd7202b479bd8d41a","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@gmail.com"},"message":"Reduce some constant duplication (#20761)

* Remove some dead code

* Decouple event priority list from event name list

* Fix lint","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/miqdigital/react/commits/77754ae6183197a63716202f71be5d396f0f2b9a"},{"sha":"a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Parallel transitions: Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions (#20672)

* Land enableTransitionEntanglement changes

Leaving the flag though because I plan to reuse it for additional,
similar changes.

* Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions

Currently we always assign the same lane to all transitions. This means
if there are two pending transitions at the same time, neither
transition can finish until both can finish, even if they affect
completely separate parts of the UI.

The new approach is to assign a different lane to each consecutive
transition, by shifting the bit to the right each time. When we reach
the end of the bit range, we cycle back to the first bit. In practice,
this should mean that all transitions get their own dedicated lane,
unless we have more pending transitions than lanes, which should
be rare.

We retain our existing behavior of assigning the same lane to all
transitions within the same event. This is achieved by caching the first
lane assigned to a transition, then re-using that one until the next

* feat(kumactl) add kumactl install crds cmd

- Introduced new `kumactl` command: `kumactl install crds`
  which will render all Custom Resource Definitions used by kuma.
  By providing `--only-missing` flag it will output content of
  CRDs which are not present in the cluster (it will use the same
  approach to get kubeconfig as `kumactl install control-plane`
  - I added small script which I will be using in helm hooks
    to generate missing CRDs. I'm doing it via script, and not by
    directly providing `entrypoint` or `cmd` to container, as there
    is logic to check if command `kumactl install crds \
     --only-missing` returns anything as if there are already
    all CRDs present the command `kubectl create -f -` would fail
    and I don't see any other, easier way to handle this case
- Added helm's pre-upgrade hook to install missing crds, which is
  using the container with `kumactl` mentioned above
- Modified helm's `values.yaml` file to reflect changes mentioned
  above

* fix(kumactl) fix sh scripts (removed function key)

Updated .golden files to reflect the new command
`kumactl install crds`

* feat(*) add helm upgrade logic to e2e framework

Introduced to our e2e tests framework functionalities to upgrade
kuma helm charts.

* fix(*) add helm repo for kuma in CI

As we currently are using our external helm repository, to install
some older versions of Kuma during the helm upgrade tests,
we have to configure helm to use this repository first

* feat(kumactl) introuce ctx to install crds command

[{"sha":"a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Parallel transitions: Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions (#20672)

* Land enableTransitionEntanglement changes

Leaving the flag though because I plan to reuse it for additional,
similar changes.

* Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions

Currently we always assign the same lane to all transitions. This means
if there are two pending transitions at the same time, neither
transition can finish until both can finish, even if they affect
completely separate parts of the UI.

The new approach is to assign a different lane to each consecutive
transition, by shifting the bit to the right each time. When we reach
the end of the bit range, we cycle back to the first bit. In practice,
this should mean that all transitions get their own dedicated lane,
unless we have more pending transitions than lanes, which should
be rare.

We retain our existing behavior of assigning the same lane to all
transitions within the same event. This is achieved by caching the first
lane assigned to a transition, then re-using that one until the next
React task, by which point the event must have finished. This preserves
the guarantee that all transition updates that result from a single
event will be consistent.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/facebook/react/commits/a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62"}]

The memoized state of effect hooks is only invalidated when deps change. Deps are compared between the previous effect and the current effect. This can be problematic if one commit consists of an update that has changed deps followed by an update that has equal deps. That commit will lead to memoizedState containing the changed deps even though we committed with unchanged deps.

The n+1 update will therefore run an effect because we compare the updated deps with the deps with which we never actually committed.

To prevent this we now invalidate memoizedState on every updateEffectImpl call so that memoizedStat.deps always points to the latest deps.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/bb1b7951d182d36345c83154f9d9bab218011b46"},{"sha":"f8b6969da65457cd18b434616cb01ac1c7b0afcc","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Add `--commit` param to release scripts (#20703)

* Concurrent Mode test for uMS render mutation

Same test as the one added in #20665, but for Concurrent Mode.

* Use double render to detect render phase mutation

PR #20665 added a mechanism to detect when a `useMutableSource` source
is mutated during the render phase. It relies on the fact that we double
invoke components that error during development using
`invokeGuardedCallback`. If the version in the double render doesn't
match the first, that indicates there must have been a mutation during
render.

At first I thought it worked by detecting inside the *other* double
render, the one we do for Strict Mode. It turns out that while it does
warn then, the warning is suppressed, because we suppress all console
methods that occur during the Strict Mode double render. So it's really
the `invokeGuardedCallback` one that makes it work.

Anyway, let's set that aside that issue for a second. I realized during
review that errors that occur during the Strict Mode double render
reveal a useful property: A pure component will never throw during the
double render, because if it were pure, it would have also thrown during
the first render... in which case it wouldn't have double rendered! This
is true of all such errors, not just the one thrown by
`useMutableSource`.

Given this, we can simplify the `useMutableSource` mutation detection
mechanism. Instead of tracking and comparing the source's version, we
can instead check if we're inside a double render when the error is
thrown.

To get around the console suppression issue, I changed the warning to an
error. It errors regardless, in both dev and prod, so it doesn't have
semantic implications.

However, because of the paradox I described above, we arguably
_shouldn't_ throw an error in development, since we know that error
won't happen in production, because prod doesn't double render. (It's
still a tearing bug, but that doesn't mean the component will actually
throw.) I considered that, but that requires a larger conversation about
how to handle errors that we know are only possible in development. I
think we should probably be suppressing *all* errors (with a warning)
that occur during a double render.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/dc27b5aaae5e1a028dc77412d5396466aaa87268"},{"sha":"7cb9fd7ef822436aef13c8cbf648af1e21a5309a","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Land interleaved updates change in main fork (#20710)

Uses download-experimental script and places the base artifacts into
a top-level folder.

Replaces the two separate sizebot jobs (one for each channel, stable and
experimental) with a single combined job that outputs size information
for all bundles in a single GitHub comment.

what I would do is remove our custom Rollup sizes plugin, and read the
sizes from the filesystem instead. We would lose some information about
the build configuration used to generate each artifact, but that can be
inferred from the filepath. For example, the filepath
`fb-www/ReactDOM-dev.classic.js` already tells us everything we need to
know about the artifact. Leaving this for a follow up.

* Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions

Currently we always assign the same lane to all transitions. This means
if there are two pending transitions at the same time, neither
transition can finish until both can finish, even if they affect
completely separate parts of the UI.

The new approach is to assign a different lane to each consecutive
transition, by shifting the bit to the right each time. When we reach
the end of the bit range, we cycle back to the first bit. In practice,
this should mean that all transitions get their own dedicated lane,
unless we have more pending transitions than lanes, which should
be rare.

We retain our existing behavior of assigning the same lane to all
transitions within the same event. This is achieved by caching the first
lane assigned to a transition, then re-using that one until the next
React task, by which point the event must have finished. This preserves
the guarantee that all transition updates that result from a single
event will be consistent.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62"},{"sha":"4793ee1966a1692e98a3005af9586b81411b4c9f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Don't shift interleaved updates to separate lane

Now that interleaved updates are added to a special queue, we no longer
need to shift them into their own lane. We can add to a lane that's
already in the middle of rendering without risk of tearing.

See #20615 for more background.

I've only changed this in the new fork, and only behind the
enableTransitionEntanglements flag.

Most of this commit involves updating tests. The "shift-to-a-new" lane
trick was intentionally used in a handful of tests where two or more
updates need to be scheduled in different lanes. Most of these tests
were written before `startTransition` existed, and all of them were
written before transitions were assigned arbitrary lanes.

So I ported these tests to use `startTransition` instead, which is the
idiomatic way to mark an update as parallel.

I didn't change the old fork at all. Writing these tests in such a way
that they also pass in the old fork actually revealed a few flaws in the
current implementation regarding interrupting a suspended refresh
transition early, which is a good reminder that we should be writing our
tests using idiomatic patterns as much as we possibly can.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/4793ee1966a1692e98a3005af9586b81411b4c9f"}]

This can be problematic if one commit consists of an update that has changed deps followed by an update that has equal deps. That commit will lead to memoizedState containing the changed deps even though we committed with unchanged deps.

The n+1 update will therefore run an effect because we compare the updated deps with the deps with which we never actually committed.

* Concurrent Mode test for uMS render mutation

Same test as the one added in #20665, but for Concurrent Mode.

* Use double render to detect render phase mutation

PR #20665 added a mechanism to detect when a `useMutableSource` source
is mutated during the render phase. It relies on the fact that we double
invoke components that error during development using
`invokeGuardedCallback`. If the version in the double render doesn't
match the first, that indicates there must have been a mutation during
render.

At first I thought it worked by detecting inside the *other* double
render, the one we do for Strict Mode. It turns out that while it does
warn then, the warning is suppressed, because we suppress all console
methods that occur during the Strict Mode double render. So it's really
the `invokeGuardedCallback` one that makes it work.

Anyway, let's set that aside that issue for a second. I realized during
review that errors that occur during the Strict Mode double render
reveal a useful property: A pure component will never throw during the
double render, because if it were pure, it would have also thrown during
the first render... in which case it wouldn't have double rendered! This
is true of all such errors, not just the one thrown by
`useMutableSource`.

Given this, we can simplify the `useMutableSource` mutation detection
mechanism. Instead of tracking and comparing the source's version, we
can instead check if we're inside a double render when the error is
thrown.

To get around the console suppression issue, I changed the warning to an
error. It errors regardless, in both dev and prod, so it doesn't have
semantic implications.

However, because of the paradox I described above, we arguably
_shouldn't_ throw an error in development, since we know that error
won't happen in production, because prod doesn't double render. (It's
still a tearing bug, but that doesn't mean the component will actually
throw.) I considered that, but that requires a larger conversation about
how to handle errors that we know are only possible in development. I
think we should probably be suppressing *all* errors (with a warning)
that occur during a double render.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/dc27b5aaae5e1a028dc77412d5396466aaa87268"},{"sha":"7cb9fd7ef822436aef13c8cbf648af1e21a5309a","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Land interleaved updates change in main fork (#20710)

The memoized state of effect hooks is only invalidated when deps change. Deps are compared between the previous effect and the current effect. This can be problematic if one commit consists of an update that has changed deps followed by an update that has equal deps. That commit will lead to memoizedState containing the changed deps even though we committed with unchanged deps.

The n+1 update will therefore run an effect because we compare the updated deps with the deps with which we never actually committed.

To prevent this we now invalidate memoizedState on every updateEffectImpl call so that memoizedStat.deps always points to the latest deps.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kaykdm/react/commits/bb1b7951d182d36345c83154f9d9bab218011b46"},{"sha":"f8b6969da65457cd18b434616cb01ac1c7b0afcc","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Add `--commit` param to release scripts (#20703)

* Concurrent Mode test for uMS render mutation

Same test as the one added in #20665, but for Concurrent Mode.

* Use double render to detect render phase mutation

PR #20665 added a mechanism to detect when a `useMutableSource` source
is mutated during the render phase. It relies on the fact that we double
invoke components that error during development using
`invokeGuardedCallback`. If the version in the double render doesn't
match the first, that indicates there must have been a mutation during
render.

At first I thought it worked by detecting inside the *other* double
render, the one we do for Strict Mode. It turns out that while it does
warn then, the warning is suppressed, because we suppress all console
methods that occur during the Strict Mode double render. So it's really
the `invokeGuardedCallback` one that makes it work.

Anyway, let's set that aside that issue for a second. I realized during
review that errors that occur during the Strict Mode double render
reveal a useful property: A pure component will never throw during the
double render, because if it were pure, it would have also thrown during
the first render... in which case it wouldn't have double rendered! This
is true of all such errors, not just the one thrown by
`useMutableSource`.

Given this, we can simplify the `useMutableSource` mutation detection
mechanism. Instead of tracking and comparing the source's version, we
can instead check if we're inside a double render when the error is
thrown.

To get around the console suppression issue, I changed the warning to an
error. It errors regardless, in both dev and prod, so it doesn't have
semantic implications.

However, because of the paradox I described above, we arguably
_shouldn't_ throw an error in development, since we know that error
won't happen in production, because prod doesn't double render. (It's
still a tearing bug, but that doesn't mean the component will actually
throw.) I considered that, but that requires a larger conversation about
how to handle errors that we know are only possible in development. I
think we should probably be suppressing *all* errors (with a warning)
that occur during a double render.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kaykdm/react/commits/dc27b5aaae5e1a028dc77412d5396466aaa87268"},{"sha":"7cb9fd7ef822436aef13c8cbf648af1e21a5309a","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Land interleaved updates change in main fork (#20710)

Co-authored-by: Kristin Laemmert <mildwonkey@users.noreply.github.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/e39abbf6f07126a03a68fcb912b9168f384310be"},{"sha":"4991cc48354275f5a190b12e0f8cdafb952fdc0a","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"cli: Improve error for invalid -target flags

Errors encountered when parsing flags for apply, plan, and refresh were
being suppressed. This resulted in a generic usage error when using an
invalid `-target` flag.

This commit makes several changes to address this. First, these commands
now output the flag parse error before exiting, leaving at least some
hint about the error. You can verify this manually with something like:

    terraform apply -invalid-flag

We also change how target attributes are parsed, moving the
responsibility from the flags instance to the command. This allows us to
customize the diagnostic output to be more user friendly. The
diagnostics now look like:

```shellsession
$ terraform apply -no-color -target=foo

Error: Invalid target "foo"

Resource specification must include a resource type and name.
```

Finally, we add test coverage for both parsing of target flags, and at

* Remove some dead code

* Decouple event priority list from event name list

* Fix lint","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/manojsdeveloper/react/commits/77754ae6183197a63716202f71be5d396f0f2b9a"},{"sha":"a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Parallel transitions: Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions (#20672)

* Land enableTransitionEntanglement changes

Leaving the flag though because I plan to reuse it for additional,
similar changes.

* Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions

Currently we always assign the same lane to all transitions. This means
if there are two pending transitions at the same time, neither
transition can finish until both can finish, even if they affect
completely separate parts of the UI.

The new approach is to assign a different lane to each consecutive
transition, by shifting the bit to the right each time. When we reach
the end of the bit range, we cycle back to the first bit. In practice,
this should mean that all transitions get their own dedicated lane,
unless we have more pending transitions than lanes, which should
be rare.

We retain our existing behavior of assigning the same lane to all
transitions within the same event. This is achieved by caching the first
lane assigned to a transition, then re-using that one until the next
React task, by which point the event must have finished. This preserves
the guarantee that all transition updates that result from a single
event will be consistent.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/manojsdeveloper/react/commits/a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62"}]

[{"sha":"72cff5951e065703d7bd7af48f959314030c8035","author":{"name":"mergify[bot]","email":"b09a6ee808b67e98a221404e7aaa52e0398a4954@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"feat(kumactl) add kumactl install crds cmd (bp #1419)

* feat(kumactl) add kumactl install crds cmd

- Introduced new `kumactl` command: `kumactl install crds`
  which will render all Custom Resource Definitions used by kuma.
  By providing `--only-missing` flag it will output content of
  CRDs which are not present in the cluster (it will use the same
  approach to get kubeconfig as `kumactl install control-plane`
  - I added small script which I will be using in helm hooks
    to generate missing CRDs. I'm doing it via script, and not by
    directly providing `entrypoint` or `cmd` to container, as there
    is logic to check if command `kumactl install crds \
     --only-missing` returns anything as if there are already
    all CRDs present the command `kubectl create -f -` would fail
    and I don't see any other, easier way to handle this case
- Added helm's pre-upgrade hook to install missing crds, which is
  using the container with `kumactl` mentioned above
- Modified helm's `values.yaml` file to reflect changes mentioned
  above

* fix(kumactl) fix sh scripts (removed function key)

Updated .golden files to reflect the new command
`kumactl install crds`

* feat(*) add helm upgrade logic to e2e framework

Introduced to our e2e tests framework functionalities to upgrade
kuma helm charts.

* fix(*) add helm repo for kuma in CI

As we currently are using our external helm repository, to install
some older versions of Kuma during the helm upgrade tests,
we have to configure helm to use this repository first

* feat(kumactl) introuce ctx to install crds command

When user supplies env-vars through kumactl, they are being added to the default list of env-vars instead of replacing them.
This fix makes sure the supplied env-vars get overridden properly if the env-var exists in default list otherwise they are added to the list.

* Create new template in _helpers.tpl and use it to generate env-vars in cp-deployment.yaml
* Update helmtemplates_vfsdata.go, since cp-deployment.yaml changed
* Update install-control-plane test cases, since generation of env-vars changed
* Add new test case in install-control-plane to test the fix

Fix #1273

(#1448)

When specifying a `kuma.io/service` with a "." DNS resolution would not work
because it would only look at the first part of the DNS name.
This would also cause `foo.bar.mesh` and `foo.mesh` to resolve to the same thing
which may give a false sense of isolation of meshes in the DNS
We now only strips the last part of the DNS name if it matches the `.mesh` domain suffix.
